value.value: The four connected cavities (hollow spaces) centrally located within the brain that connect posteriorly with the central canal of the spinal cord.
The determination of the presence of actual or potential neoplastic tissue which has been left outside the boundary of a resected specimen within the patient.

label.value: Liter Divided by Milligram Per Day

value.value: A unit of concentration equal to liter per milligram per day.

label.value: Liter Divided by Milligram per Meter Squared

value.value: A unit of concentration equal to one liter divided by the derived denominator milligram per square meter.

label.value: Liter Divided by Microgram per Day

value.value: A unit of concentration equal to one liter divided by the derived denominator microgram per day.

label.value: Mean Carbon Monoxide Diffusing Capability Test

value.value: The mean volume of the carbon monoxide that is transferred from inspired gas into the pulmonary capillary blood.

label.value: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Forced Vital Capacity in 6 Seconds

value.value: A calculated ratio of the forced expiratory volume in one second to the largest observed expired volume during the first six seconds of a forced vital capacity (FVC) maneuver.
The volume of oxygen consumed by the body per heartbeat while at rest.

The measurement of the ability of the lung to store energy, which is required for passive expiration. Reactance consists of two components: the negative component reflects capacitive behavior (C) and corresponds to both the thoraco-pulmonary elasticity and to changes in the available lung volumes in the distal compartments of the lung; the positive component of reactance has inertial characteristics (I) describing the moving air column in the bronchial tree.

The ratio of the amount of carbon dioxide produced to the amount of oxygen consumed in one breath. This ratio is used to estimate the respiratory quotient, which indicates what type of fuel source the body is metabolising to provide energy.
A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC).
The slender tubular part of the hypophysial diverticulum; the stalk of Rathke's pocket.
The rate at which oxygen is absorbed and utilized by any given tissue in the body.
The absence of change in the overall attenuation of the metastasis and in the peripheral rim, suggesting a lack of response to treatment.
The amount of cancer antigen 125 is reduced by 50% from protocol-defined baseline value(s).
The amount of cancer antigen 125 is reduced by 75% from protocol-defined baseline value(s).
The disappearance of all signs of cancer based on physical exam, such as palpation.

The disappearance of cancer in response to treatment, including platelet and white blood cell counts returning to normal levels, a non-palpable spleen, and no immature white blood cells present in the blood unless it is a regenerating marrow following treatment.
A decrease in the size and the extent of tissue involvement by cancer, based on physical exam, such as palpation.
The disappearance of all signs of cancer, based on CT scan and criteria-defined assessments.
The disappearance of all signs of cancer, including the absence of a detectable disease-related genetic abnormality, as determined by techniques such as karyotyping or FISH, in response to treatment.
A minimal decrease in abnormal karyotype, based on pre-defined thresholds.

Lymph nodes found within the head and neck region of the body, which drain into the deep cervical nodes, either directly or indirectly. These include the occipital, mastoid, parotid, facial, retropharyngeal, submandibular, submental, lingual and cervical lymph nodes. Any lymph node located in the head or neck.
A minor decrease in abnormal karyotype, based on pre-defined thresholds.
No change in abnormal karyotype, based on pre-defined thresholds.
A partial decrease in abnormal karyotype, based on pre-defined thresholds.
A conversion from one disease diagnosis to another, which may be considered a progression to a worsening state.
No new lesions(s) and a decrease in tumor size, or a reduction in central necrosis or attenuation in one or more enhancing lesions, based on pre-defined thresholds.
An improvement in erythrocyte count as a response to treatment.
An improvement of neutrophil count as a response to treatment.
An improvement of platelet count as a response to treatment.

The disappearance of all signs of cancer, supported by the absence of phenotypically aberrant plasma cells (clonal) in bone marrow. (Rajkumar SV, Harousseau J, Durie B et al, Consensus recommendations for the uniform reporting of clinical trials: report of the International Myeloma Workshop Consensus Panel 1. Blood. 2011; 117(18):4691-4695)
A response that is neither favorable nor unfavorable.
Any lymph node within the thoracic cavity.
A major decrease in signs of cancer, supported by pathological examination and based on pre-defined thresholds.
A decrease in the number of bone marrow plasma cells to protocol-defined level(s).
A minor decrease in signs of cancer, supported by pathological examination and based on pre-defined thresholds.
The disappearance of all signs of cancer, supported by molecular analysis.
A decrease in signs of cancer, supported by molecular analysis.
The disappearance of all signs of cancer, supported by morphological analysis.

label.value: Morphologic Complete Remission with Incomplete Blood Count Recovery

value.value: The disappearance of all cells with morphologic characteristics of cancer, accompanied by incomplete bone marrow recovery, as evidenced by persistent anemia, thrombocytopenia or neutropenia.

The disappearance of all cells with morphologic characteristics of leukemia, accompanied by bone marrow recovery, in response to treatment. Hematologic recovery is not required. Leukemia free state can be a hypocellular marrow.
A finding indicating that there is an improvement in the measures of disease burden, meeting a predetermined threshold, but not meeting partial response criteria.
Following a previous assessment of progressive disease unconfirmed (PDu) of non-target lesion(s), the subsequent required assessment does not confirm progressive disease.

A preparation of bacterial lysate with potential immunomodulatory activity. Staphage lysate, obtained by phage lysis of Staphylococcal aureus, may be used as an antigenic stimulus to elicit non-specific humoral and cellular immune responses.
Any lymph node within the abdomen.
No apparent change or worsening in lesion staging classification.
Hypo-attenuation of the metastases which may appear pseudocystic, perfectly homogeneous, and devoid of a recognizable peripheral rim.
Mixed attenuation and some homogeneity of the metastases with a partially resolved peripheral rim.
The disappearance of all signs of cancer, supported by pathological examination.
